  "text": "Although carrion consumption plays a similar functional role in terrestrial and aquatic food webs, several fundamental differences exist in scavenging dynamics among these ecosystem types due to the unique selection pressures imposed by the physical properties of water and air. In particular, the limited role of bacteria and temporal stability of environmental conditions on the sea floor appears to have facilitated the evolution of a much more diverse community of macrofauna that relies on carrion for a higher portion of its nutrient consumption than is present in terrestrial ecosystems. Nonetheless, despite the additional constraints of scavenging on land, carrion consumption is pervasive among macrofauna in terrestrial ecosystems (DeVault et al. 2003, Selva and [CITATION_1] , suggesting that scavenging is a vital means of acquiring nutrients for many species regardless of their functional role in food webs.",
